Light

Light casts light and shadows onto a 3D scene

Lights illuminate surfaces to add highlights and atmosphere to scenes. You can use lights to create atmosphere and guide players to the intended path.

Shadows can add character to a location and limit player visibility in dark areas.

This guide also covers GIProbe and BakedLightmap, which rely on other Light nodes in the scene to show off their features.

In this guide, we’ll show you how to:

  • Light a scene.
  • Adjust and animate lights.
  • Make a light react to player input.
  • Create a day-night cycle with real-time shadows.

Overview of Light nodes

Here is a quick overview of all the available light nodes:

  • OmniLight
  • SpotLight
  • DirectionalLight
  • GIProbe
  • BakedLightmap

OmniLight emits light in a sphere away from its position.

SpotLight emits light in a cone from its position.

DirectionalLight emits light across the entire scene. Its rotation determines the light and shadow direction. Ideally, there only needs to be one DirectionalLight per scene. This light is ideal for simulating sunlight or making simple scene-wide lighting.

GIProbe creates real-time global illumination. It bakes indirect light from geometry with the Use In Baked Light property enabled and projects it onto dynamic objects. It looks great but runs the slowest of all the lighting options.

BakedLightMap creates pre-calculated, raytraced lighting. Using other lights, it creates textures known as lightmaps to add lighting details on top of mesh textures. It’s pre-calculated and runs fast in-game, at the cost of increasing your project’s file size.

Setting up a Light

Besides adding any of the above light nodes, all light needs geometry to reflect the light. You can use MeshInstance and its Mesh resource to get geometry for your level.

You can then add a light such as OmniLight, and enable shadows by setting Shadow -> Enabled to true.

Shadows need a surface to appear on. You can create a simple surface using a MeshInstance with a plane mesh. Then have other meshes above to cast shadows onto the plane.

Light’s key features

Here are some key features to use when using any light in 3D.

Energy determines the strength of the light, which you can animate to create flickering effects.

0.5 Energy 2.5 Energy 10.0 Energy

Color changes the light color cast onto the world. A more-saturated color drastically affects the appearance of surrounding materials.

Shadow -> Enabled casts dynamic shadows behind objects. Dynamic shadows reduce performance but prevent light from reaching interior areas.

Shadows have many properties. You can find specifics about shadows in Troubleshooting.

Energy, Shadow, and Color are properties available to all light nodes.

Note: The following properties only apply to OmniLight and SpotLight:

Range determines how far the light reaches. It also affects how far shadows can reach within the light’s bounds.

Range 5 Range 10 Range 60

Attenuation is a curve that changes how the light fades out as it approaches the light’s Range.

Attenuation 1 Attenuation 0.1 Attenuation 5

Note: Nodes extending the class Light are dynamic lights. Unlike static lights, you can move these lights and the surrounding world updates to match. You can only produce dynamic shadows from dynamic lights.

How to use a Light in practice

Now we can look at some concrete examples of using lights in a 3D scene.

Lighting an outdoor scene

DirectionalLight is ideal for representing sunlight. If your scene has a WorldEnvironment with a ProceduralSky or a PanoramaSky, you can use the 3D viewport to align the DirectionalLight to the sun’s angle.

To align the DirectionalLight to the sun, select the DirectionalLight, move the Camera, so the sun is in the center of the screen, then select Align Rotation With View in the Perspective menu in the 3D Viewport:

You can also press Ctrl+Alt+F as a shortcut for the same operation.

Lastly, you need to offset DirectionalLight by 180 degrees, which points at the ground rather than toward the sun.

You can also enable shadows, so the sun’s direction casts shadows onto the scene.

Creating a day-night cycle

Some games like Breath of the Wild and Grand Theft Auto show the passage of time with a day-night system. The strength, color, and direction of the lighting change as time passes.

In Godot, you can simulate changing sunlight during the day using a DirectionalLight and an AnimationPlayer.

Creating animation tracks on the Rotation, Light Color, and Light Energy properties of a DirectionalLight lets you decide the sun angle, color, and strength during the day.

You can create a short looping animation and use the AnimationPlayer playback speed to slow it down.

We chose an animation length of twenty-four seconds, so each second represents an hour of the day. This scale makes it easier to apply real-world references of color and time to the system.

The angles we used for the sun are as follows:

  • 0 seconds - Vector3(90, 20, 0)
  • 6 seconds - Vector3(0, 20, 0)
  • 12 seconds - Vector3(-90, 20, 0)
  • 18 seconds - Vector3(-180, 20, 0)
  • 24 seconds - Vector3(-270, 20, 0)

The rotation of 20 degrees on the y-axis acts as our sun’s longitude, so the shadows don’t align with the world’s z-axis. The increments of 90 degrees make the sun rotate consistently without the need for quaternions or code.

The sunlight and ambient light colors are up to you, depending on your game’s visual design. You can see the demo project for exact values.

Another challenge is getting the sun in the sky.

You can add a child Sprite3D to the DirectionalLight, which holds the sun as a billboarding QuadMesh. When you offset the node’s Translation and enable Billboard and Fixed Size on the mesh material, the sun appears consistently sized in the sky.

You can enable shadows on this DirectionalLight to get shadows that match the sun’s angle.

Look to the Troubleshooting section for helpful tips on fixing visual bugs with real-time shadows. The process for generating DirectionalLight shadows is different in Godot 4 to provide accurate-looking results with less configuration.

The final step for a convincing day-night system is to change the color of the sky. We can use a Viewport with a ColorRect using a GLSL shader to create a sky that quickly changes color.

A ProceduralSky resource isn’t fit for this job since it’s less customizable and is slow to update every frame. We chose a PanoramaSky with a ViewportTexture instead to utilize the speed of GLSL shaders.

As shown below, using a Viewport creates a render target. The ColorRect renders the GLSL shader.

The PanoramaSky resource in a WorldEnvironment can point to a ViewportTexture to create a dynamic sky.

The GLSL shader can expose two colors for us to change in code.

Here is the shader we used on the ColorRect:

shader_type canvas_item;

uniform vec4 sky_color: hint_color = vec4(1.0);
uniform vec4 horizon_color: hint_color = vec4(vec3(0.48),1.0);

uniform float horizon_top_height = 0.35;
uniform float horizon_bottom_height = 0.4;

void fragment(){
    // Only the top half of the shader is above the 3D horizon.
    float compressed_y = smoothstep(horizon_top_height, horizon_bottom_height, UV.y);

    vec3 sky = mix(sky_color.xyz, horizon_color.xyz, vec3(compressed_y));
    COLOR = vec4(sky, 1.0);
}

Then using GDScript in the main scene, we can update the shader parameters to match the colors set earlier on the AnimationPlayer.

onready var _camera_pivot: Spatial = $CameraPivot

onready var _sky_shader: ShaderMaterial = $Viewport/SkyColor.material
onready var _environment: Environment = $WorldEnvironment.get_environment()
onready var _sun_light: DirectionalLight = $SunLight
onready var _sun_sprite: MeshInstance = $SunLight/Sun


func _process(delta: float) -> void:
    _sun_sprite.get_active_material(0).albedo_color = _sun_light.get_color()

    var ambient_light_color: Color = _environment.get_ambient_light_color()
    _sky_shader.set_shader_param("sky_color", ambient_light_color.lightened(0.8))
    _sky_shader.set_shader_param("horizon_color", ambient_light_color)

    _camera_pivot.rotate_y(ROTATION_SPEED * delta)

More AnimationPlayer tracks could replace this code, but maintaining two sets of colors for sunlight and ambient light is enough to get a decent-looking result.

Note: Godot offers a ProceduralSky resource to generate a sky texture. However, updating a ProceduralSky is performance-intensive and not adapted to real-time use.

To learn more about using Viewport and ViewportTexture, check out the Viewport guide.

Lighting an interior scene

In real life, light bounces around objects, transferring their color to nearby surfaces and creating subtle light gradients in shadowed areas.

The GIProbe node helps you simulate that in your games, including on moving objects. The GIProbe pre-calculates light information in a game area and allows the graphics engine to fake light bounces at a reasonable performance cost.

On the image below, notice the red and yellow leaking onto the wall.

Compared to BakedLightmap, GIProbe gives higher-quality results with smaller file sizes, and it also works on moving objects. However, the catch is GIProbe requires more graphics processing power compared to BakedLightmap.

If you add a GIProbe without any setup, it only changes the dynamic range of nearby lights. Its power comes from blending static lighting with dynamic lighting.

To use GIProbe’s static lighting, add the node to a scene and adjust its Extents to fit the area to light up.

You need to enable Baked Light -> Use In Baked Light on every static mesh that should contribute to the global illumination.

Then you can select the GIProbe again and click Bake GI Probe in the Toolbar to begin the bake.

Static lighting only remains accurate if all the baked lights and meshes don’t move. If you move any baked meshes, the scene’s lighting can appear incorrect.

If you update your levels’ design, you’ll need to bake the corresponding GI probes again.

You can use GI probes for indoor and outdoor scenes. However, the Extents box makes it easier to segment indoor scenes into several probes: one probe per room.

Enabling the Interior property removes the energy from the sky in its light calculations. GIProbe nodes account for any DirectionalLight in the scene set to bake so that you can get sunlight in an interior scene like the one shown below.

You can edit the scale of this box with the Extents property, and move the GIProbe to adjust its position.

The lighting quality gets lower with larger Extents, but you can regain the quality lost from having larger extents by increasing the Subdiv property. It is worth noting you don’t need a GIProbe to cover your whole level, and you can use multiple probes just in areas of interest.

After setting the bounds of a GIProbe or BakedLightmap, you can temporarily hide the appearance of bounds using the View -> Gizmos menu in the Toolbar.

Making a flashlight

Flashlights allow players to explore dark areas, creating tension as they explore their surroundings.

You can create dark scenes by adding a WorldEnvironment node and giving it an Environment. The default environment settings plunge the world into darkness.

Using an FPS character controller, we can parent a MeshInstance and a SpotLight onto the player’s Camera (or the parent node that it follows) to explore places in the dark.

You can turn the flashlight on or off using an AnimationPlayer to animate the light energy of the SpotLight.

To make the shadows look more dramatic, we can offset the flashlight’s position and rotation to make the shadow angle stand out dramatically apart from the camera angle.

Lastly, enable shadows on the SpotLight. In Godot 3.x, spotlight shadows often appear to have bias problems unless you enable Shadow -> Reverse Cull Face.

Shooting out lights with a gun

Some games like Thief let you shoot out lights to hide your trail from patrolling enemies.

In Godot, you can make lights respond to player events using signals and collisions, which use an AnimationPlayer to change the light’s appearance once the event has occurred.

For the light bulbs, we used a StaticBody with a CollisionShape, SpotLight, and AnimationPlayer, so it registers as a physics body when the player’s gun RayCast hits it.

Our laser beam gun uses a RayCast node and checks for collisions when shooting. We use duck-typing to ensure the body has the take_damage() method. If so, we call the function.

    var target: Vector3
    var direction: Vector3
    if _camera_ray.is_colliding():
        var body = _camera_ray.get_collider()
        if body.has_method("take_damage"):
            body.take_damage()
        target = _camera_ray.get_collision_point()
        direction = target + _camera_ray.get_collision_normal()
    else:
        target = _camera_ray.to_global(_camera_ray.cast_to)
        direction = global_transform.origin
    _cast_beam(target, direction)

The body has a script to set up properties to animate groups of particles and switch the animation to “shot” instead of “idle.”

onready var _animation_player: AnimationPlayer = $AnimationPlayer
onready var _collision_particles: Spatial = $CollisionParticles
onready var _light_meshes: Spatial = $LightMeshes
onready var _spot_light: SpotLight = $SpotLight

Here’s the take_damage() function that gets called. The AnimationPlayer plays the “shot” animation once if it takes damage and ensures the light can’t play the animation twice.

func take_damage() -> void:
    if _is_broken:
        return

    _is_broken = true
    _animation_player.play("shot")
    for particles in _collision_particles.get_children():
        particles.emitting = true

If you’re instancing these lights as .tscn files like us, you may want to ensure the Mesh and its material are Local To Scene. Otherwise, all fluorescent lights animate at the same time, as they share the same Mesh resource.

You can split up the level mesh or increase the light limit in Project Settings with Max Lights Per Object at the cost of longer shader loading times.

Triggering light on gunfire

You can activate a light when shooting for added feedback and flair.

Using an OmniLight, you can animate the Energy property to make it flash. An AnimationPlayer is one way to animate the property, but a Tween is also a good fit.

You can use an input action to restart the AnimationPlayer, triggering the light:

onready var _animation_player: AnimationPlayer = $Player/AnimationPlayer


func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("shoot_3d"):
        _animation_player.stop(true)
        _animation_player.play("shoot")

If you want to learn more about making the gun shoot at objects, read the guide on RayCast nodes.

Your questions

What are the major differences between all the lighting options?

You’ll often combine light nodes like OmniLight with either BakedLightmap for low-end devices or GIProbe on high-end devices.

Here is a table comparing the different features of lighting options in Godot 3.x.

Feature Dynamic Lights BakedLightmap GIProbe
Updates at runtime ✓ ✓
Supports indirect lighting ✓ ✓
Runs well on low-end devices ✓ ✓
Increases project file size ✓ ✓
Renders real-time shadows ✓

The main benefit of BakedLightmap over GIProbe is its low-performance cost. All baked lighting data gets saved as a texture. This increases file size fairly, but it runs well on older mobile devices or low-end computers.

BakedLightmap can also capture some lighting information about the game world to enhance your game’s look with dynamic objects at runtime. However, this can appear less accurate than the dynamic lighting provided by a GIProbe with low-quality settings.

Which lighting option is best for my project?

BakedLightmap provides static, pre-rendered lighting. This is great for getting good-looking lighting on low-end GPUs, at the cost of larger file size to store the lightmap textures.

GIProbe provides real-time results but requires baking to get started, increasing the project file size. This is still less than what BakedLightmap requires. The main downside for GIProbe is that it’s hard to get good performance on low-end GPUs without sacrificing quality.

Dynamic lighting ( OmniLight, DirectionalLight, SpotLight) is fast on low-end GPUs with only a few lights.

You’re limited to 32 lights per surface. Levels that use more lights should split up the level meshes or increase the Max Lights Per Object in Project Settings at the cost of longer shader compile times.

If you want maximum performance, use BakedLightmap as much as possible, with dynamic lights and especially fewer lights casting shadows in real-time.

For more dynamic lighting, you can use the GIProbe node and combine lights. To ensure your game runs well, you’ll always have to test rendering performance on your project’s slowest target hardware.

Troubleshooting

Shadow Issues

Suppose there’s a distance between your shadows and your objects. In that case, you can reduce the Shadow Bias, increase the Contact slider, or increase the available Shadow Atlas Texture size, so your shadows are more accurate to the space they’re trying to fill.

If you have lots of artifacts on SpotLight and DirectionalLight, enable Reverse Cull Face. It increases the distance between your mesh and the shadow, but it helps reduce banding.

Godot 4.0 plans to have improved real-time shadows that look sharper and more accurate without requiring as much adjusting.

BakedLightmap Bugs

No lighting appears on my model after baking the scene

All bakeable meshes must come from an ArrayMesh. You can generate a second set of UV coordinates called UV2 to render light information to texture with these resources in the editor.

If a mesh doesn’t appear affected by BakedLightmap, you might still need to unwrap the UV2 in the 3D Toolbar. After baking, you can check if BakedLightmap included your model by viewing the .png or .exr texture generated by the BakedLightmap.

Baking is taking forever

If you imported a mesh with a large scale, Godot gives it a lightmap size hint that matches the scale. The lightmap size hint won’t adjust to the new in-game scale if you scale the mesh down in Godot instead of your modeling software.

You can fix this by adjusting the lightmap size hint to a smaller value, like 64 on both axes.

Visible bands on baked lighting

If the baked light is banding, you can increase the Dynamic Range property, check HDR, or uncheck Color, so the banding is less noticeable.

If the baked light is super low-resolution and blocky, there are a few solutions:

  • Minimize UV2 space for unbaked areas.
  • Increase lightmap hint on the mesh.
  • Don’t re-use baked meshes at wildly different scales. The light texture scales with the mesh, and if its resolution is too small, you’ll start to see stretched pixels.

Seams appear on the models

If you see seams on mesh corners, there are two solutions:

  • Extend baked faces past their corners.
  • Seal up the area behind the wall with solid light “blockers” set to bake.

Dynamic Lighting Bugs

Too many lights in the scene

If there are too many lights in your scene, causing you to reach Godot’s limit, you have a few options:

Consider using BakedLightmap to bake light nodes that don’t move. For each light, set Bake Mode -> All instead of Bake Mode -> Indirect to free up the dynamic light budget.

Alternatively, use a single DirectionalLight to cover your level. Enabling shadows prevents this light from reaching interior spaces.

Dark blue low-contrast lighting

If there’s low-contrast lighting in your scene:

  • Use a WorldEnvironment, and reduce Ambient -> Sky Contribution.
  • Introduce a DirectionalLight.
  • Use BakedLightmap or GIProbe.

Pro Tips

You can get more accurate static lighting by sizing the Extents past the room’s geometry. This is an engine limitation as light beyond the extents is immediately cut off, leading to artifacts and dark spots.

The names of GIProbe, BakedLightmap, and ReflectionProbe are changing in Godot 4.0: https://github.com/godotengine/godot/pull/49325

Real-time shadows need to use the project’s Shadow Atlas. This is a texture that holds shadow data important to the Camera. You can increase the shadow atlas size from a default value of 2048 to get clearer-looking real-time shadows.

If you’re casting long shadows using a DirectionalLight, you can reduce the Shadow Max Distance to free up more space on the shadow atlas. This leads to closer shadows appearing to look sharper. This only works because all real-time shadows share the same shadow atlas texture.

You can let Godot set the lightmap size hint for you to match Godot’s unit scale.

You can also adjust the lightmap size defaults in Import options.

Each model has a Lightmap Size Hint, which controls this, and can help improve or scale back on lightmap shadow quality for certain models.

A model’s lightmap hint contributes to the total size of the lightmap texture for each BakedLightmap node. If one model’s lightmap hint is huge, every other model fights for space within the data of a single BakedLightmap node.

This is where you can try to make trade-offs in lightmap quality between models, or up the texture resolution of the lightmap in the BakedLightmap properties, under Atlas -> Max Size.

You can turn off BakedLightmap’s Capture property if everything in your scene is static since it only lights dynamic objects to save file size.

Godot generates DirectionalLight shadows in real-time onto a project-wide texture called the Shadow Atlas. Each DirectionalLight gets its own Shadow Atlas.
